<h2>Chapter 5: White Label Margins. The Scalability Unlock &#123;#ch5&#125;</h2>
<p>White labeling is one of the most underused revenue models in agency economics. It is also one of the most structurally powerful.</p>
<p>Under a white label model, the agency sells services to clients but outsources actual delivery to a third-party provider. The client sees only the agency's branding. The agency keeps the markup between what it charges and what it pays for delivery.</p>
<h3>How White Label Works in Practice</h3>
<p>Here is a concrete example:</p>
<ol>
<li>Agency sells an SEO retainer to a client for $3,000/month</li>
<li>Agency outsources content production to a <a href="/blog/white-label-seo-content/">white label SEO content provider</a> for $1,200/month</li>
<li>Agency manages the client relationship and reporting ,  5 hours at $100/hour = $500</li>
<li>Net margin: $3,000 - $1,200 - $500 = <strong>$1,300/month per client (43% net margin)</strong></li>
</ol>
<p>Scale that to 20 clients and you have $26,000/month in net margin from one service line, without adding a single employee.</p>
